tional under-20 football team|Netherlands Antilles U20]] |nationalteam2 = [[Netherlands national under-19 football team|Netherlands U19]] |nationalyears1 = 2007–2008 |nationalyears2 = 2009–2010 |nationalcaps1 = 5 |nationalcaps2 = 10 |nationalgoals1 = 3 |nationalgoals2 = 1 |nationalyears3 = 2011–2013 |nationalteam3 = [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands U21]] |nationalcaps3 = 10 |nationalgoals3 = 1 |nationalyears4 = 2016– |nationalteam4 = [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao]] |nationalcaps4 = 19 |nationalgoals4 = 9 |club-update = 21:46, 26 February 2019 (UTC) |nationalteam-update = 13:41, 23 January 2019 (UTC) }} '''Leandro Jones Johan Bacuna''' (born 21 August 1991) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays for Welsh club [[Cardiff City|Cardiff City ]] as a [[midfielder]] and [[Defender (association football)|right back]]. Bacuna was capped 20 times at youth levels for the Netherlands and also represented the [[Netherlands Antilles national football team|Netherlands Antilles]] at youth level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2015/03/24/aston-villas-leandro-bacuna-hoping-for-international-future-with/|title=Aston Villa's Leandro Bacuna hoping for international future with the Netherlands}}</ref> Bacuna represents the [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao national team]], the successor side to the Netherlands Antilles, and won the [[2017 Caribbean Cup]] with the side in July 2017.
==Club career==
===Groningen=== On 30 October 2009, Bacuna made his first team debut for [[FC Groningen|Groningen]] in an [[Eredivisie]] match against [[PSV Eindhoven|PSV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vi.nl/Spelers/Speler.htm?employer=57&season=382&dbid=63150&typeofpage=84137|title=Cookies op VI.nl}}</ref> Bacuna has also played for Groningen's youth teams. On 6 November 2009, he scored his first goal for the first team in a league match against [[Heracles Almelo]], an eventual 4–1 victory for Groningen.<ref>[http://politiken.dk/sport/fodbold/article815651.ece Holland, Æresdivisionen&nbsp;– Politiken.dk] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027031438/http://politiken.dk/sport/fodbold/article815651.ece |date=2009-10-27 }}</ref>
===Aston Villa=== It was announced on 13 June 2013 that Bacuna had signed a three-year contract with [[Premier League]] club [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]. Handed the number 7 shirt, Bacuna impressed many with his debut season for the Villains, despite constantly playing out of position at right back.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vi.nl/nieuws/242500/Groninger-Bacuna-wordt-collega-van-Vlaar-in-Engeland.htm|title=Cookies op VI.nl}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~3209128,00.html|title=Bacuna tipped to be|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130615161605/http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10265~3209128%2C00.html|archivedate=2013-06-15|df=}}</ref> Bacuna scored his first Premier League goal on 28 September at home to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. His second goal came from a free-kick in the claret and blues' 2–0 victory over [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]]. He continued his goalscoring run with goals against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C|West Bromwich Albion]], [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich]]. {{citation needed|date=December 2014}}
In the [[2014–15 Aston Villa F.C. season|2014–15 season]], however, Bacuna found it harder to break into the starting line-up, starting just one game in the [[2014–15 Premier League|Premier League]]. On 15 February 2015, he scored the first of two Villa goals in the fifth round of the [[2014–15 FA Cup|FA Cup]] in a 2–1 win over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]], taking the club into the quarter-finals.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}
On 20 August 2015, Bacuna signed a new long-term contract with the club.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/34006797"Leandro Bacuna: New long-term Aston Villa deal for Dutchman"] BBC Sport. 20 August 2015. Retrieved 20 August 2015.</ref>
===Reading=== On 13 August 2017, Bacuna moved to [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], signing a four-year contract.<ref name="Reading Sign Bacuna">{{cite web|title=Bacuna joins the Royals!|url=https://www.readingfc.co.uk/news/2017/august/bacuna-joins-the-royals/|publisher=Reading F.C.|accessdate=13 August 2017|date=13 August 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Reading in an [[EFL Cup]] tie against [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on 22 August 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40932153 |title=Reading 3–1 Millwall |publisher=BBC |date=22 August 2017 |accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref>
===Cardiff City=== On 31 January 2019, Bacuna moved to Premier League side [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], signing a four-and-a-half year deal for a transfer fee believed to be around £3 million.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cardiffcityfc.co.uk/news/2019/january/deadline-day-bacuna-is-a-bluebird/ |title=Deadline Day: Bacuna is a Bluebird |publisher=Cardiff City F.C. |date=31 January 2019 |accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/transfers/cardiff-city-transfer-news-deadline-day-rumours-today-epl-leandro-bacuna-a8757036.html |title=Leandro Bacuna signs in £3m deal from Reading |newspaper=The Independent |last=Blanche |first=Phil |date=31 January 2019 |accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref>
==International career== Born in the Netherlands to parents of Curaçaoan descent, Bacuna played for the [[Netherlands Antilles national football team|Netherlands Antilles under-20]] side, as well as various youth Dutch teams. He received his first [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao national team]] call-up in March 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2016/03/17/aston-villa-defender-leandro-bacuna-gets-first-senior-internatio/|title=Aston Villa defender Leandro Bacuna gets first senior international call-up for Curacao}}</ref> earning his first cap in a 1–0 loss to [[Barbados national football team|Barbados]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://readastonvilla.com/2016/03/28/villans-international-duty-part-1-2/|title=Villans on international duty – Part One|date=28 March 2016}}</ref> {{clear}}
==Personal life== He is the older brother of professional footballer [[Juninho Bacuna]].<ref>http://nos.nl/artikel/2036079-ook-tweede-bacuna-wint-de-beker.html</ref>
